<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-12-18T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-12-18T06:00:00-05:00" n="347" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d347">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1320</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_RPS1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Reinsch</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-12-18T19:00:00+08:00">
                                <hi rend="italic">December 18, 1914, 7 p.m.</hi>
                            </date>
                            <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 10:30 a.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>Items for the information of the Department. There is a serious
                            controversy between Japanese and Chinese, former demanding right to
                            appoint customs officials Tsingtao, latter unwilling to relinquish power
                            of appointment though ready to name Japanese officials. Aglen is much
                            concerned as question involves unity of customs service.</p>
                        <p>Consul General at Mukden reports that six regiments of Japanese troops
                            [are] to be stationed at Mukden.</p>
                        <p>The Japanese commander in chief Tsingtao expressed American [military
                            attachés?] visiting there that he had been expecting return of American
                            Consul for some time.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_RPS1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Reinsch</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>